    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-10-05T16:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-09-27T17:00:00-05:00" n="409"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d409">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.111 Refugee Children/109</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Belgian Ambassador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Van der Straten-Ponthoz</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="42" xml:id="d409fn42">Undated; received in the Department on October 5,
                        1942.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates"
                        calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1942-10-05T23:59:59+02:00"
                        notBefore="1942-09-28T00:00:00+02:00">undated</date>
                </dateline>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">D. 8406</seg>
                    <lb/>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 5955</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I understand that Your Excellency has submitted
                    to President Roosevelt a plan concerning the transfer to the United States of
                    four or five thousand children of different nationalities, such as Belgians,
                    Dutch, Czecoslovaquians and etc., who would remain in this country until the end
                    of hostilities.</p>
                <p>However, according to my information, the American Government wishes to obtain,
                    beforehand, from the interested governments, the assurance that these children
                    will be permitted to return to their respective countries after the war.</p>
                <p>As far as children sent from Belgium are concerned, I can give Your <pb
                        facs="0488" n="476" xml:id="pg_476"/> Excellency assurances that Belgian
                    authorities will authorize the children of Belgian nationality to reenter
                    Belgium at the termination of their sojourn in the United States.</p>
                <p>I avail myself [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">R. v. Straten</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
